en:
Grade:  B
Reason:  This observance is actually a pretty good idea as an awareness day.  We want to make it possible for as many people as possible to function independently on this planet, and Braille brings literacy to people who cannot read visual writing.  I am very pleased that Israel has become fairly accommodating for the blind.  Not only do we get things like Braille labels in elevators, but our crosswalks have foot-readable cues, tactile maps, and auditory cues of when it is and is not safe to cross.  The last is useful even for sighted people, who have more to do than just stare at traffic lights, so considering the needs of one segment of the population may benefit others as well.  The biggest problem with this observance is one which plagues most of them:  lack of publicity.  UN observances mostly get reported occasionally in the news (if at all) and listed on sites dedicated to observances and holidays; very few have gotten attention on their own.  If the UN actually got its act together and promoted World Braille Day, its grade would be A.
Created by the World Blind Union and UN General Assembly
